article.headline: Baylor 63, Iowa State 59
article.story: WACO, Texas (AP) -- Poor shooting and losing the rebound battle create a bad combination on the road. Those two factors provided Baylor all the advantage it needed in a 63-59 win over Iowa State on Saturday night. "Baylor played very hard tonight, give them a lot of credit, they played a hell of a game," said Cyclones head coach Wayne Morgan. "We shot very poorly tonight and got outrebounded. If we can't hold our own on the boards, we're not going to win on the road." Despite giving the Bears (6-11, 1-3 Big 12) a 42-33 advantage on the boards and hitting only 44 percent from the field (24 of 54), the Cyclones staged a late rally. The Bears led 54-46 with just over three minutes to play, but five consecutive free throws by Jake Sullivan and Jackson Vroman's layup closed the gap to 54-53 less than a minute later. But Iowa State (11-4, 2-2 Big 12) never pulled within a single point again, and Baylor's Carl Marshall iced the victory with a pair of free throws in the game's final two seconds. The loss extended the Cyclones' Big 12 losing streak on the road to 19 games. Meanwhile, Baylor coach Scott Drew got his first conference win. "I'm excited not to hear, 'Are you going to win a game in the Big 12?' anymore," he said. Curtis Stinson led the Iowa State scoring with 16 points, while Vroman contributed 12. Baylor's scoring was paced by Corey Herring with 16 points and Harvey Thomas, who added 12. "This was a big win, and we were prepared for it," Thomas said. "This was a great opportunity to gain confidence in the Big 12. If teams don't bring their 'A game,' then they are going to walk out of here with a loss." Baylor outscored Iowa State 16-8 to open the second half and led 37-28 with just more than 14 minutes left to play. The Cyclones closed the margin to four points at 39-35, but the Bears went on a 9-2 run and extended their lead to 48-37 at the 8:22 mark. Neither team shot well in the game's early stages. With just under eight minutes remaining, the Cyclones led 10-8 and had connected on only three of 11 attempts from the field. Baylor fared even worse against the Iowa State zone defense with a 4-of-20 shooting performance. The Cyclones moved in front 18-13 with three and half minutes left to play. But the Bears went on an 8-2 run and led at the half 21-20 despite hitting only eight of 29 field goal attempts.
